Women rarely enjoy equal protections as women in most countries around the world. Legislation in Chile that prohibited gender discrimination in housing was passed in 1996, but only 55% of women have subrogated their housing rights to the husband, as the law requires.^2 Chile has the highest rate of working women without adequate social security among Latin American countries.^2 Spain (1997) and Chile (1999) are the only countries in Latin America with laws that entitle survivors of rape to an abortion.^2 Chile has an abortion law^3 which provides that an abortion may be performed at the request of the woman if the woman’s life or her physical or mental health are in danger, if the fetus’ health is jeopardized or if the pregnancy resulted from sexual assault. Nevertheless, Chilean law does not allow abortion in any situation of incest or rape or where the pregnancy is the result of jeopardy to the woman’s health, through medical diagnosis made during pregnancy, unless this danger is to the woman’s life.^2

Chile has experienced some improvements in women’s health status, as reflected in the country’s high life expectancy, lower maternal mortality and stillbirth rates and improvements in women’s income participation. Nevertheless, a large socioeconomic disparity separates women in the third and fourth quintiles of Chilean women from those in the first and second quintiles, regarding every recent health indicator.^2
